# mm/page_alloc.ad
#
# Mirrors mm/page_alloc.c in Linux at the key API surface: order-based
# allocation of contiguous page runs (2^order × 4 KiB) via alloc_pages
# / free_pages, fed by the early memblock allocator underneath. Each
# free run lives on its order's free list with the next-free pointer
# stored in the run's first 8 bytes (Linux's `struct page` would hold
# this on the side; we keep it intrusive for now to dodge the need for
# a memmap[] backing array).
#
# Design choices (M16.15):
#
#   - MAX_ORDER = 10  → up to 1024 contiguous pages = 4 MiB per request.
#   - alloc_pages(order) tries this order's free list, then splits a
#     higher-order block (recursive), then falls back to a fresh
#     memblock_alloc for a properly-aligned chunk.
#   - free_pages(addr, order) returns a run AND coalesces: if the freed
#     run's XOR-buddy at the same order is also free, the pair is merged
#     into one order-(N+1) block and the merge repeats up to MAX_ORDER
#     (the canonical __free_one_page algorithm from mm/page_alloc.c). The
#     buddy is located by scanning that order's free list (_try_remove_buddy)
#     rather than a per-page memmap[] — being present on the list IS the
#     "this buddy is free, same-order, and managed" predicate, so no
#     separate in-range/zone guard is needed: only allocator-managed runs
#     ever reach a free list, and each run is wholly within one memblock
#     region, so a merged pair is always physically-contiguous RAM (two
#     XOR-buddies in different regions force those regions to abut exactly
#     at the buddy boundary). This keeps large high-order allocations
#     serviceable over a long uptime instead of fragmenting.
#
# This sits between the early bump allocator (mm/memblock.ad) and the
# slab allocator (mm/slab.ad): slab uses order-0 single pages, the
# large-kmalloc path in slab.ad uses order >0 for blocks > 2 KiB.

from mm.memblock import memblock_alloc, memblock_region_top, memblock_can_alloc
from mm.cow import cow_boot_cr3, cow_refcount, cow_drop_page
from kernel.printk.printk import printk1, printk2
# #mm-parity: reset a frame's struct-page descriptor (LRU membership,
# rmap, flags, mapcount) when it is freed, so a later re-allocation of the
# same PFN never inherits stale reclaim bookkeeping (a freed page still
# linked on the inactive LRU would corrupt the list).
from mm.page import page_reset, page_pfn, page_phys, page_test_flag, PG_LRU
from mm.lru import lru_remove

# CR3 primitives for the boot-CR3 guard below (assembly intrinsics,
# same externs kernel/sched/core.ad and mm/vma.ad declare).
extern def local_irq_save() -> uint64
extern def local_irq_restore(flags: uint64)
extern def read_cr3() -> uint64
extern def load_cr3(value: uint64)

# Lower bound of allocator-managed RAM (the page allocator's floor set by
# e820_init: kernel_image_end() rounded to the memblock start). Any masked
# free-list link BELOW this is provably not an allocator-owned page. Used
# by the free-list integrity guard below to reject a scribbled pointer
# BEFORE it is dereferenced.
extern def kernel_image_end() -> uint64

# SMP buddy-allocator lock (root-cause fix for the intermittent whole-
# system hard freeze after a spawn/reap-heavy operation — e.g. a 3-stage
# `echo | cat | grep` pipeline whose stages exit and are reaped on two
# CPUs at once). Every free list in this file (free_pages_order[]) is
# SHARED global state with an INTRUSIVE next-link in the freed chunk's
# first 8 bytes; alloc_pages / free_pages / _try_remove_buddy all read-
# modify-write it. The boot-CR3 guard masks IRQs LOCALLY but gives ZERO
# cross-CPU mutual exclusion, so two CPUs in the allocator at once race
# the non-atomic list splices: a lost/duplicated link cross-links or
# self-cycles a free list, and the next _try_remove_buddy walk loops
# forever with IRQs masked (the boot-CR3/local_irq_save window) — timer
# dead, console half-emitted, box wedged. This was the dominant cause of
# the pipeline hang on SMP (UP, where the allocator is naturally
# serialised, never reproduced it). A single global spinlock around the
# free-list critical section is sufficient: alloc/free are short and the
# contention window is tiny. Held INSIDE the existing IRQ-off + boot-CR3
# window so lock-hold time is bounded and an IRQ can never observe the
# borrowed CR3 mid-splice.
extern def spinlock_lock(ptr: Ptr[uint32])
extern def spinlock_unlock(ptr: Ptr[uint32])
_pa_buddy_lock: uint32 = 0

# SMP region-pool lock (root-cause fix for the concurrent-execve phys-region
# reuse race). The large-region allocator below (region_alloc / region_free,
# used by fs/elf.ad for every loaded ELF image + interp) keeps per-size
# free-list buckets whose heads AND the intrusive next-link in each pooled
# chunk are SHARED global state read-modify-written on every alloc/free. The
# boot-CR3 guard masks IRQs LOCALLY but gives ZERO cross-CPU exclusion, so
# two CPUs doing execve at once both popped the same bucket head (or both
# cold-missed into memblock_alloc), handing the identical physical image
# region to two address spaces (observed: both got phys 0x0a849000). A
# single global spinlock around the bucket RMW — held INSIDE the existing
# IRQ-off + boot-CR3 window, exactly like _pa_buddy_lock — closes it. Lock
# ordering: region_lock is never held while taking buddy_lock and vice
# versa; the memblock_alloc cold-miss taken under region_lock is a leaf
# (memblock has its own inner lock), so there is no deadlock.
_pa_region_lock: uint32 = 0

PAGE_SIZE:  uint64 = 4096
PAGE_SHIFT: int32  = 12
MAX_ORDER:  int32  = 10            # 2^10 pages = 1024 = 4 MiB

# --- BOOT-CR3 GUARD --------------------------------------------------
#
# Every free list in this file is INTRUSIVE: the `next` link lives in
# the first 8 bytes of the free chunk itself and is read/written
# through a raw PHYSICAL-address pointer (cast[Ptr[uint64]](phys)).
# That is only correct when phys X is identity-mapped at VA X in the
# CURRENT CR3. Hamnix has no kernel-half direct map of RAM
# (phys_to_virt covers the high-half image only), so these accesses
# rely on the identity mapping — which a USER CR3 does not guarantee:
# a native task's image/stack/brk window is identity-mapped at its
# pool phys range, and after an rfork/fork COW crack those user VAs
# point at DIFFERENT frames. A link store at "phys" X issued while
# such a CR3 is live lands in the task's own COW page instead; a link
# load reads user data. The free lists cross-link or self-cycle, and
# the next _try_remove_buddy walk spins forever with IRQs masked —
# the observed whole-system lockup after `enter linux` exits were
# reaped (QEMU regdump: CPU0 at _try_remove_buddy, IF=0, user CR3).
#
# Fix at the allocator layer: every public entry point that touches a
# free-list link runs its body under the PRISTINE BOOT CR3, which
# identity-maps ALL of RAM by construction (the same guard
# _free_task_user_pagetables uses for its raw-physical walk). IRQs
# are masked across the borrowed-CR3 window so no interrupt handler
# can observe it. The switch is skipped when the live CR3 already IS
# the boot root (early boot, kthreads, callers like task_reap that
# batch under the guard themselves) — then the wrap costs two reads.
_PA_CR3_MASK: uint64 = 0x000FFFFFFFFFF000

# One free list per order. Each slot is the head address of that order's
# free chain (0 if empty); each free run carries its next-free pointer
# in the first 8 bytes of its own memory.
free_pages_order: Array[11, uint64]

# Diagnostics: pages ever pulled from memblock at any order.
nr_pages_total:   uint64 = 0
# Pages currently sitting on order-0's free list (subset of total).
# Higher-order free lists are not counted yet; the metric is mostly
# useful for the existing order-0 smoke test.
nr_pages_free:    uint64 = 0
# Cumulative pages returned to the allocator via free_pages. The
# current in-use count is (nr_pages_total - nr_pages_freed_total)
# once the buddy allocator is fully up. Monotonically increasing.
nr_pages_freed_total: uint64 = 0


# --- free-list integrity guard (QA-N37) ----------------------------
#
# ROOT-CAUSE CATCHER for the intermittent `#GP vec=0x0d` in
# _alloc_pages_raw on `mov rax,[rax]` under heavy memory pressure. That
# fault is a wild dereference of a CORRUPTED free-list pointer: a page
# sitting on a buddy free list had its intrusive `next` link (its first 8
# bytes) SCRIBBLED — by a use-after-free (a task still writes a page after
# it was freed to the buddy allocator), a double-free (the same run pushed
# onto a list twice, then handed out and overwritten while still linked),
# or a stray wild kernel write landing on a free page. The corruption is
# committed silently at free/UAF time and only detonates much later when
# an unrelated allocation pops the poisoned head.
#
# The guard makes the corrupting event self-announcing and non-fatal:
#
#   * Every freed run carries, in ADDITION to its next-link at [0], a
#     position-derived CANARY at [8] == addr ^ _PA_CANARY. The canary is a
#     pure function of the run's own address, so legitimate unlink writes
#     (which only rewrite [0]) never disturb it — but ANY foreign write
#     into a still-free page (a UAF/double-free scribble that clobbers the
#     first cache line) corrupts it. Checked on every pop/walk.
#   * Every link is bounds-validated (_pa_link_ok) before being
#     dereferenced: a valid link is NULL or a page-aligned physical address
#     inside [floor, top). A scribbled non-canonical / sub-floor / user-VA
#     pointer is caught HERE, before the faulting `mov rax,[rax]`.
#   * On detection the guard LOGS the offending page + bad value + order
#     and SELF-HEALS by truncating the list at the corruption point (or
#     ignoring a detected double-free push), so the box survives with a
#     diagnostic instead of hard-halting on the wild deref. Truncation can
#     strand the tail of one list — a bounded leak, never a fault.
#
# This is a permanent guard: it stays on the hot path (two extra word
# accesses + a cached-bounds check per link op) and converts a mysterious
# one-shot halt into a precise, attributable report the moment a bad free
# happens.
_PA_CANARY: uint64 = 0x9A1EDEADF2EE1000

# Cached allocator RAM bounds (populated lazily on first use; both are
# fixed once early boot has enumerated memblock, so a one-shot cache
# avoids re-scanning the region list on every hot-path link op).
_pa_ram_floor_cache: uint64 = 0
_pa_ram_top_cache:   uint64 = 0


def _pa_ram_floor() -> uint64:
    if _pa_ram_floor_cache == 0:
        _pa_ram_floor_cache = kernel_image_end()
    return _pa_ram_floor_cache


def _pa_ram_top() -> uint64:
    if _pa_ram_top_cache == 0:
        _pa_ram_top_cache = memblock_region_top()
    return _pa_ram_top_cache


def _pa_link_ok(addr: uint64) -> int32:
    # A valid intrusive free-list link is either NULL (end of list) or a
    # page-aligned physical address inside allocator-managed RAM. Anything
    # else is a scribbled pointer we must NOT dereference.
    if addr == 0:
        return 1
    if (addr & 0xFFF) != 0:
        return 0
    floor: uint64 = _pa_ram_floor()
    if floor != 0 and addr < floor:
        return 0
    top: uint64 = _pa_ram_top()
    if top != 0 and addr >= top:
        return 0
    return 1


def _pa_set_next(node: uint64, next_val: uint64):
    # Push-side link store: the intrusive next-link at [0] plus the
    # position-derived canary at [8]. Callers guarantee `node` is a real
    # page-aligned run of at least one page (>= 16 bytes), so [8] is in
    # bounds and is dead memory until the run is re-allocated.
    cast[Ptr[uint64]](node)[0] = next_val
    cast[Ptr[uint64]](node + 8)[0] = node ^ _PA_CANARY


def _pa_get_next(node: uint64, order: int32) -> uint64:
    # Pop/walk-side link load. Verifies the canary (catches a page written
    # while free — UAF / double-free) and the link value (catches a
    # scribbled pointer) BEFORE returning. On any failure, logs the
    # corrupting event with full context and SELF-HEALS by returning 0
    # (truncate the list here) so the kernel never faults on a wild deref.
    canary: uint64 = cast[Ptr[uint64]](node + 8)[0]
    if canary != (node ^ _PA_CANARY):
        printk2("[pa-corrupt] page %p scribbled while free (UAF/double-free) order=%d\n",
                node, cast[uint64](order))
        printk2("[pa-corrupt]   canary=%p expected=%p — truncating free list\n",
                canary, node ^ _PA_CANARY)
        return 0
    nxt: uint64 = cast[Ptr[uint64]](node)[0]
    if _pa_link_ok(nxt) == 0:
        printk2("[pa-corrupt] page %p has wild next-link %p — truncating free list\n",
                node, nxt)
        return 0
    return nxt


# --- order-N alloc / free ------------------------------------------

def alloc_pages(order: int32) -> uint64:
    # Returns a page-aligned base address of 2^order contiguous 4 KiB
    # pages, or 0 on OOM. Caller "owns" the entire run until they
    # call free_pages(addr, order). Boot-CR3 guard: see header above —
    # the free-list link loads/stores in _alloc_pages_raw must resolve
    # through a CR3 that identity-maps all of RAM.
    _ap_live: uint64 = read_cr3()
    _ap_irq: uint64 = local_irq_save()
    _ap_boot: uint64 = cow_boot_cr3()
    _ap_sw: int32 = 0
    if _ap_boot != 0 and (_ap_boot & _PA_CR3_MASK) != (_ap_live & _PA_CR3_MASK):
        load_cr3(_ap_boot)
        _ap_sw = 1
    # SMP mutual exclusion over the shared free lists (see _pa_buddy_lock).
    # Inside the IRQ-off + boot-CR3 window: this CPU cannot be preempted
    # while holding the lock, so a remote CPU only ever spins on it for the
    # short list-splice and never deadlocks against an IRQ handler.
    spinlock_lock(&_pa_buddy_lock)
    ret: uint64 = _alloc_pages_raw(order)
    spinlock_unlock(&_pa_buddy_lock)
    if _ap_sw != 0:
        load_cr3(_ap_live)
    local_irq_restore(_ap_irq)
    return ret


def _alloc_pages_raw(order: int32) -> uint64:
    # Body of alloc_pages; must run under an identity-mapping CR3
    # (the public wrapper guarantees it). nr_pages_free is bumped
    # along every code path that adds/removes from order-0's free
    # list so the counter stays consistent across split / merge /
    # direct free.
    if order < 0:
        return 0
    if order > MAX_ORDER:
        return 0

    # Path 1: this order's free list has a ready run.
    o: uint64 = cast[uint64](order)
    head: uint64 = free_pages_order[o]
    if head != 0:
        # Integrity guard: a corrupted list head is the exact source of the
        # QA-N37 `mov rax,[rax]` #GP. Validate it BEFORE dereferencing;
        # if it is wild, log and drop the poisoned list rather than fault,
        # then fall through to the split / memblock paths.
        if _pa_link_ok(head) == 0:
            printk2("[pa-corrupt] order-%d free-list head is wild: %p — dropping list\n",
                    o, head)
            free_pages_order[o] = 0
        else:
            free_pages_order[o] = _pa_get_next(head, order)
            if order == 0:
                nr_pages_free = nr_pages_free - 1
            return head

    # Path 2: split a higher-order run into two halves of this order;
    # return one half, put the other half on this order's free list.
    # (Recurse on the RAW body — the wrapper already holds the guard.)
    if order < MAX_ORDER:
        higher: uint64 = _alloc_pages_raw(order + 1)
        if higher != 0:
            half: uint64 = PAGE_SIZE << o
            buddy: uint64 = higher + half
            _pa_set_next(buddy, free_pages_order[o])
            free_pages_order[o] = buddy
            if order == 0:
                nr_pages_free = nr_pages_free + 1
            return higher

    # Path 3: fresh allocation from memblock. Size and alignment must
    # both be the full run width so the address is correctly aligned
    # for the order-0 split that may follow.
    size: uint64 = PAGE_SIZE << o
    page: uint64 = memblock_alloc(size, size)
    if page == 0:
        return 0
    pages_in_run: uint64 = cast[uint64](1) << o
    nr_pages_total = nr_pages_total + pages_in_run
    return page


def _try_remove_buddy(target: uint64, order: int32) -> int32:
    # Scan the order-N free list for `target` (which is meant to be
    # this freeing block's buddy). If found, unlink and return 1.
    # O(list length) — fine while lists stay short; replace with a
    # struct-page-style buddy bit when fragmentation pressure grows.
    o: uint64 = cast[uint64](order)
    head: uint64 = free_pages_order[o]
    if head == 0:
        return 0
    # Integrity guard: never walk from a wild head (QA-N37).
    if _pa_link_ok(head) == 0:
        printk2("[pa-corrupt] order-%d buddy-scan head wild: %p — dropping list\n",
                o, head)
        free_pages_order[o] = 0
        return 0
    if head == target:
        free_pages_order[o] = _pa_get_next(head, order)
        return 1
    prev: uint64 = head
    cur:  uint64 = _pa_get_next(head, order)
    while cur != 0:
        if cur == target:
            # Unlink: prev.next = cur.next (validated read + canaried write).
            _pa_set_next(prev, _pa_get_next(cur, order))
            return 1
        prev = cur
        cur  = _pa_get_next(cur, order)
    return 0


def free_pages(addr: uint64, order: int32):
    # Return a run to the allocator. Boot-CR3 guard: see header above —
    # the buddy-merge walk and the free-list push in _free_pages_raw
    # must resolve through a CR3 that identity-maps all of RAM.
    _fp_live: uint64 = read_cr3()
    _fp_irq: uint64 = local_irq_save()
    _fp_boot: uint64 = cow_boot_cr3()
    _fp_sw: int32 = 0
    if _fp_boot != 0 and (_fp_boot & _PA_CR3_MASK) != (_fp_live & _PA_CR3_MASK):
        load_cr3(_fp_boot)
        _fp_sw = 1
    # SMP mutual exclusion over the shared free lists (see _pa_buddy_lock).
    spinlock_lock(&_pa_buddy_lock)
    _free_pages_raw(addr, order)
    spinlock_unlock(&_pa_buddy_lock)
    if _fp_sw != 0:
        load_cr3(_fp_live)
    local_irq_restore(_fp_irq)


def _free_pages_raw(addr: uint64, order: int32):
    # Body of free_pages; must run under an identity-mapping CR3 (the
    # public wrapper guarantees it). If the freed run's buddy at the
    # same order is already free, MERGE them into a single order-(N+1)
    # block and recurse; this is the canonical buddy algorithm (mirrors
    # __free_one_page in mm/page_alloc.c). Stops at MAX_ORDER.
    if addr == 0:
        return
    if order < 0 or order > MAX_ORDER:
        return

    # Accounting: track cumulative pages freed. The difference
    # (nr_pages_total - nr_pages_freed_total) gives the pages currently
    # in active use — a useful leak probe after spawn/reap cycles.
    freed_pages: uint64 = cast[uint64](1) << cast[uint64](order)
    nr_pages_freed_total = nr_pages_freed_total + freed_pages

    # #mm-parity: clear each freed frame's struct-page descriptor so no
    # stale LRU link, rmap entry, or dirty/anon flag survives into the next
    # allocation of the same PFN.  A frame that was an LRU member but is
    # freed by a path OTHER than the reclaimer (task exit, COW break, munmap)
    # would otherwise leave a dangling node on the inactive list.
    rp_base_pfn: uint64 = page_pfn(addr)
    rp_i: uint64 = 0
    while rp_i < freed_pages:
        rp_pfn: uint64 = rp_base_pfn + rp_i
        # If the frame is still on an LRU list, UNLINK it properly (fixing
        # the neighbours' links + the head/tail anchors) before zeroing the
        # descriptor — a bare reset would leave dangling neighbour links.
        if page_test_flag(rp_pfn, PG_LRU) != 0:
            lru_remove(page_phys(rp_pfn))
        page_reset(rp_pfn)
        rp_i = rp_i + 1

    cur_addr:  uint64 = addr
    cur_order: int32  = order
    while cur_order < MAX_ORDER:
        run_size: uint64 = PAGE_SIZE << cast[uint64](cur_order)
        buddy:    uint64 = cur_addr ^ run_size
        if _try_remove_buddy(buddy, cur_order) == 0:
            break
        # Merged. Canonical "parent" block is the lower of the two,
        # which is `addr & ~(run_size << 1)` aligned. cur_addr ^ run_size
        # gives buddy; AND with ~run_size canonicalises.
        if buddy < cur_addr:
            cur_addr = buddy
        # If order == 0 we just consumed a free order-0 entry too,
        # adjust the free-count accordingly.
        if cur_order == 0:
            nr_pages_free = nr_pages_free - 1
        cur_order = cur_order + 1

    # Push the (possibly merged) block onto its order's free list.
    o: uint64 = cast[uint64](cur_order)
    # Integrity guards (QA-N37) at the free SOURCE:
    #   * a wild base address means a caller freed a bogus pointer — never
    #     splice it onto a list (it would become the next wild head).
    #   * cur_addr already at the head is an unambiguous double-free — the
    #     canary would catch it later, but rejecting it here keeps the list
    #     acyclic and names the event at the moment it happens.
    if _pa_link_ok(cur_addr) == 0:
        printk2("[pa-corrupt] free of wild addr %p order=%d — ignoring\n",
                cur_addr, cast[uint64](cur_order))
        return
    if cur_addr == free_pages_order[o]:
        printk2("[pa-corrupt] double-free of %p at order=%d — ignoring\n",
                cur_addr, cast[uint64](cur_order))
        return
    _pa_set_next(cur_addr, free_pages_order[o])
    free_pages_order[o] = cur_addr
    if cur_order == 0:
        nr_pages_free = nr_pages_free + 1


def count_free_at_order(order: int32) -> uint64:
    # Walk one order's free list and count entries. Used by the
    # M16.23 smoke test to demonstrate buddy merging. Not on a hot
    # path so the O(N) walk is fine. Boot-CR3 guard: the link walk
    # reads through raw physical pointers.
    if order < 0 or order > MAX_ORDER:
        return 0
    _cf_live: uint64 = read_cr3()
    _cf_irq: uint64 = local_irq_save()
    _cf_boot: uint64 = cow_boot_cr3()
    _cf_sw: int32 = 0
    if _cf_boot != 0 and (_cf_boot & _PA_CR3_MASK) != (_cf_live & _PA_CR3_MASK):
        load_cr3(_cf_boot)
        _cf_sw = 1
    n: uint64 = 0
    p: uint64 = free_pages_order[cast[uint64](order)]
    while p != 0:
        if _pa_link_ok(p) == 0:
            break
        n = n + 1
        p = _pa_get_next(p, order)
    if _cf_sw != 0:
        load_cr3(_cf_live)
    local_irq_restore(_cf_irq)
    return n


# --- order-0 convenience aliases (backwards-compat with M16.8) -----

def alloc_page() -> uint64:
    return alloc_pages(0)


def free_page(page: uint64):
    free_pages(page, 0)


# --- large freeable region allocator (ELF images) ------------------
#
# The ELF loader (fs/elf.ad) needs one contiguous physical region per
# loaded binary, sized to the binary's whole PT_LOAD span (memsz —
# code + data + BSS). For a big native binary like hpm that span is
# ~14.7 MiB, well above the buddy allocator's MAX_ORDER (4 MiB), so it
# historically came straight from memblock_alloc() — which is a ONE-WAY
# bump allocator with no free path. Every spawn therefore permanently
# leaked its whole image region; after ~6 `hpm` spawns the ~238 MiB
# memblock pool was exhausted and the next sys_spawn's region alloc
# returned 0 -> ENOEXEC -> hamsh reported "command not found".
#
# This allocator gives those regions a reclaim path WITHOUT a full
# buddy/slab rewrite. Backing memory still comes from memblock on a
# cold miss, but a region_free() returns the chunk to a general free
# list that the next region_alloc() reuses.
#
# WHY A GENERAL (ANY-SIZE) FREE LIST, NOT EXACT-SIZE BUCKETS (#106 leak):
# the original pool kept one free-list bucket PER EXACT byte size. That
# only recycles when the SAME binary is respawned at the IDENTICAL span.
# But the desktop launches ~28 DISTINCT native apps whose image spans
# differ by a few KiB each (16.78 MiB, 16.79 MiB, 16.92 MiB, 16.97 MiB,
# 17.90 MiB, 19.03 MiB ...). A freed 16.79 MiB chunk sat in its own
# exact-size bucket and could NOT satisfy the next 16.97 MiB request, so
# region_alloc cold-missed into memblock every time — the ONE-WAY bump
# cursor climbed monotonically (measured: 568 MiB drained across the DE
# storm, 21 of 27 allocs cold-missing) until memblock_alloc returned 0 →
# `elf: OOM` → boot wedge. The exact-size pool also STRANDED every pooled
# chunk in a bucket no differently-sized request could ever touch.
#
# The fix: a single ADDRESS-SORTED free list. region_alloc does first-fit
# (the first chunk large enough) and SPLITS the remainder back onto the
# list; region_free COALESCES with address-adjacent free neighbours so
# split fragments re-merge into whole regions. Now ANY freed region backs
# ANY later request ≤ its size, so a spawn→exit→reap cycle is NET-NEUTRAL
# on memblock headroom (the reaped image chunk is handed straight to the
# next spawn regardless of the exact span) and the pool stays flat.
#
# Each free chunk is self-describing: its first 16 bytes (dead memory
# until reused) hold [0]=next-chunk phys (0 = end), [8]=chunk byte size.
# All chunks are page-aligned and page-multiple-sized (memblock aligns
# 4096; rsize is page-rounded; splits preserve both), so the header
# always fits and neighbour tests are exact.

_region_free_head: uint64 = 0     # lowest-addr free chunk (0 = empty)


def _region_link_get(chunk: uint64) -> uint64:
    return cast[Ptr[uint64]](chunk)[0]


def _region_link_set(chunk: uint64, nxt: uint64):
    cast[Ptr[uint64]](chunk)[0] = nxt


def _region_size_get(chunk: uint64) -> uint64:
    return cast[Ptr[uint64]](chunk + 8)[0]


def _region_size_set(chunk: uint64, sz: uint64):
    cast[Ptr[uint64]](chunk + 8)[0] = sz


def region_alloc(size: uint64) -> uint64:
    # Allocate a page-aligned contiguous region of `size` bytes that can
    # later be returned via region_free(addr, size). Reuses a pooled
    # chunk (first-fit, splitting the remainder back onto the free list)
    # if one is big enough; otherwise carves a fresh chunk from memblock.
    # Returns 0 on OOM.
    if size == 0:
        return 0
    rsize: uint64 = (size + 4095) & ~cast[uint64](4095)
    # The free list + intrusive header are shared RMW state. Run the WHOLE
    # critical section (list walk, split, cold-miss carve) under IRQ-off +
    # boot-CR3 (for the raw-physical header deref) + the SMP region lock so
    # no two CPUs ever hand out the same chunk or race the splice.
    _ra_live: uint64 = read_cr3()
    _ra_irq: uint64 = local_irq_save()
    _ra_boot: uint64 = cow_boot_cr3()
    _ra_sw: int32 = 0
    if _ra_boot != 0 and (_ra_boot & _PA_CR3_MASK) != (_ra_live & _PA_CR3_MASK):
        load_cr3(_ra_boot)
        _ra_sw = 1
    spinlock_lock(&_pa_region_lock)
    ret: uint64 = 0
    got: int32 = 0
    # First-fit: the first free chunk whose size >= rsize.
    prev: uint64 = 0
    cur:  uint64 = _region_free_head
    while cur != 0 and got == 0:
        csz: uint64 = _region_size_get(cur)
        if csz >= rsize:
            nxt: uint64 = _region_link_get(cur)
            rem: uint64 = csz - rsize
            if rem != 0:
                # Split: hand back the low rsize bytes, re-insert the
                # remainder [cur+rsize, rem) in cur's sorted slot.
                remc: uint64 = cur + rsize
                _region_size_set(remc, rem)
                _region_link_set(remc, nxt)
                if prev == 0:
                    _region_free_head = remc
                else:
                    _region_link_set(prev, remc)
            else:
                # Exact fit: unlink cur entirely.
                if prev == 0:
                    _region_free_head = nxt
                else:
                    _region_link_set(prev, nxt)
            ret = cur
            got = 1
        else:
            prev = cur
            cur = _region_link_get(cur)
    if got == 0:
        # Cold miss: carve fresh from memblock (one-way bump; self-locks).
        ret = memblock_alloc(rsize, 4096)
    spinlock_unlock(&_pa_region_lock)
    if _ra_sw != 0:
        load_cr3(_ra_live)
    local_irq_restore(_ra_irq)
    return ret


def region_can_alloc(size: uint64) -> int32:
    # NON-MUTATING pre-check: returns 1 if region_alloc(size) would succeed
    # right now, else 0. Mirrors region_alloc's two supply sources EXACTLY:
    # a pooled free-list chunk whose size >= rsize, OR a cold-miss carve from
    # memblock (one contiguous 4 KiB-aligned run >= rsize). Because memblock
    # is a per-region bump allocator, a request only fits if ONE region holds
    # it — memblock_can_alloc encodes that (NOT the summed headroom).
    #
    # #112 execve atomicity: do_execve calls this BEFORE it tears the outgoing
    # COW image down, so an image whose contiguous region_alloc would OOM past
    # the point-of-no-return is rejected with -ENOMEM while the caller's
    # address space is still fully intact (Linux execve-failure semantics),
    # instead of the fork-child resuming into now-unmapped inherited code.
    if size == 0:
        return 0
    rsize: uint64 = (size + 4095) & ~cast[uint64](4095)
    _rc_live: uint64 = read_cr3()
    _rc_irq: uint64 = local_irq_save()
    _rc_boot: uint64 = cow_boot_cr3()
    _rc_sw: int32 = 0
    if _rc_boot != 0 and (_rc_boot & _PA_CR3_MASK) != (_rc_live & _PA_CR3_MASK):
        load_cr3(_rc_boot)
        _rc_sw = 1
    spinlock_lock(&_pa_region_lock)
    ok: int32 = 0
    cur: uint64 = _region_free_head
    while cur != 0 and ok == 0:
        if _region_size_get(cur) >= rsize:
            ok = 1
        cur = _region_link_get(cur)
    spinlock_unlock(&_pa_region_lock)
    if _rc_sw != 0:
        load_cr3(_rc_live)
    local_irq_restore(_rc_irq)
    if ok == 0:
        # No pooled chunk fits; would region_alloc cold-miss into memblock?
        if memblock_can_alloc(rsize, 4096) != 0:
            ok = 1
    return ok


def region_free(addr: uint64, size: uint64):
    # Return a region to the general free list for reuse by ANY later
    # region_alloc <= its size. Inserts address-sorted and coalesces with
    # the immediate physical neighbours so split fragments re-merge.
    if addr == 0 or size == 0:
        return
    rsize: uint64 = (size + 4095) & ~cast[uint64](4095)
    # DIAG (frame-lifetime hunt): scan the region for frames that are still
    # COW-tracked (cow_refcount > 0). If any are, returning this region to
    # the reuse pool hands a frame back to region_alloc while a forked
    # relative still COW-maps it -> the fork+exec corruption. Count + report.
    _rf_diag_n: uint64 = 0
    _rf_diag_off: uint64 = 0
    while _rf_diag_off < rsize:
        if cow_refcount(addr + _rf_diag_off) > 0:
            _rf_diag_n = _rf_diag_n + 1
        _rf_diag_off = _rf_diag_off + 4096
    if _rf_diag_n != 0:
        printk2("[rfdiag] region_free addr=%p has COW-live frames=%d\n",
                addr, _rf_diag_n)
    # Raw physical header writes: boot-CR3 guard; the sorted-insert +
    # coalesce runs under the SMP region lock so a concurrent region_alloc
    # can't observe a torn list.
    _rf_live: uint64 = read_cr3()
    _rf_irq: uint64 = local_irq_save()
    _rf_boot: uint64 = cow_boot_cr3()
    _rf_sw: int32 = 0
    if _rf_boot != 0 and (_rf_boot & _PA_CR3_MASK) != (_rf_live & _PA_CR3_MASK):
        load_cr3(_rf_boot)
        _rf_sw = 1
    spinlock_lock(&_pa_region_lock)
    # Locate the sorted insertion point: prev = highest chunk below addr.
    prev: uint64 = 0
    cur:  uint64 = _region_free_head
    while cur != 0 and cur < addr:
        prev = cur
        cur = _region_link_get(cur)
    # Coalesce backward: prev immediately precedes addr -> extend prev.
    merged_back: int32 = 0
    if prev != 0 and prev + _region_size_get(prev) == addr:
        _region_size_set(prev, _region_size_get(prev) + rsize)
        addr = prev
        rsize = _region_size_get(prev)
        merged_back = 1
    # Coalesce forward: cur immediately follows addr -> absorb cur.
    if cur != 0 and addr + rsize == cur:
        cur_next: uint64 = _region_link_get(cur)
        rsize = rsize + _region_size_get(cur)
        _region_size_set(addr, rsize)
        if merged_back != 0:
            # addr == prev, already linked; just skip past cur.
            _region_link_set(prev, cur_next)
        else:
            # addr takes cur's slot in the sorted list.
            _region_link_set(addr, cur_next)
            if prev == 0:
                _region_free_head = addr
            else:
                _region_link_set(prev, addr)
    elif merged_back == 0:
        # No coalesce: insert addr between prev and cur.
        _region_size_set(addr, rsize)
        _region_link_set(addr, cur)
        if prev == 0:
            _region_free_head = addr
        else:
            _region_link_set(prev, addr)
    spinlock_unlock(&_pa_region_lock)
    if _rf_sw != 0:
        load_cr3(_rf_live)
    local_irq_restore(_rf_irq)


def region_free_cow_safe(addr: uint64, size: uint64):
    # COW-SAFE region reclaim (fork+exec refcount-poison fix). The ELF
    # image and PT_INTERP (ld.so) images are REGIONS, not VMAs, and were
    # historically returned to the region pool via a raw region_free() at
    # task_reap — a free path that NEVER consulted the per-PFN COW refcount
    # table. But do_clone COW-shares the whole image + interp span into
    # every fork child (vm_cow_share_all / vm_cow_share_range bump each
    # present frame 0->2), and a child's execve teardown only drops its OWN
    # reference (2->1), so the OWNER's image/interp frames sit at refcount
    # >= 1 for the rest of its life. The old raw region_free then pooled
    # those frames with a STALE non-zero refcount: the next region_alloc
    # handed the poisoned chunk to a fresh image/interp load, and the first
    # time one of its frames was COW-shared, cow_share_page saw cur != 0 and
    # bumped N->N+1 instead of 0->2 — so a later cow_drop's arithmetic was
    # off-by-the-stale-count and a frame was freed while still COW-mapped
    # elsewhere (or a live relative's frame was reused). That is the
    # fork+exec corruption that scribbles a forked shell's stack canary /
    # exit-handler list (dash SIGABRT / "stack smashing detected" on
    # `dash -c /bin/true`). This is the exact class the brk (vma_free_
    # reserved_range) and user-stack (43684804) reclaims already close;
    # the image/interp region_free was the last raw-free hole.
    #
    # Drop THIS owner's COW reference on every frame BEFORE pooling:
    #   * untracked frame (refcount 0, never forked) -> cow_drop is a no-op
    #     (stays 0); the region pools exactly as before — the common case.
    #   * owner-only frame (refcount 1, child already exec'd/reaped) ->
    #     cow_drop 1->0 clears the stale count so the pooled frame is clean.
    #   * frame a LIVE relative still COW-maps (refcount >= 2) -> cow_drop
    #     2->1 keeps it for that relative; the region is NOT safe to pool
    #     (its frames are in use), so we drop the pooling and let the last
    #     relative free the frames through its own COW teardown. A rare,
    #     bounded region-address leak — never a use-after-free.
    # SAFE-FALLBACK (dfd59371 live-task use-after-free): NEVER return a
    # region to the reuse pool if ANY of its frames was EVER COW-shared
    # (refcount > 0). Correctness over a bounded address leak.
    #
    # WHY the earlier still_live>0-only guard was not enough: an identity-
    # mapped NATIVE image lives in LOW RAM the buddy allocator also
    # manages, and under app-spawn load a live relative's image frame is
    # momentarily untracked (refcount 0) or owner-only (refcount 1) at the
    # instant a sibling tears down — so pooling a region whose frames were
    # ever shared could hand a frame a LIVE relative still maps back to
    # region_alloc, aliasing two tasks onto the same physical .text and
    # dropping the live task's mapping (code=139, US=0 / cleared PTE). By
    # refusing to pool ANY once-shared region we make that reuse impossible.
    #
    # Drop THIS owner's per-PFN COW reference on every tracked frame first
    # (so a fork relative's reclaim is not stranded at a stale count / the
    # parent's frame is never left over-counted), then:
    #   * region had NO tracked frame (never forked) -> pool it as before
    #     (the overwhelmingly common case: a task that never fork+exec'd a
    #     child leaks nothing).
    #   * region had ANY tracked frame -> LEAK the region address (do not
    #     pool). The frames are still reclaimed as raw RAM at reboot; the
    #     only cost is that this exact region span is not reused. Never a
    #     use-after-free.
    if addr == 0 or size == 0:
        return
    rsize: uint64 = (size + 4095) & ~cast[uint64](4095)
    any_cow: int32 = 0
    off: uint64 = 0
    while off < rsize:
        frame: uint64 = addr + off
        if cow_refcount(frame) > 0:
            any_cow = 1
            cow_drop_page(frame)
        off = off + 4096
    if any_cow == 0:
        # No frame was ever COW-shared: the region is genuinely private and
        # free — pool it for reuse.
        region_free(addr, rsize)


# --- bring-up + stats ----------------------------------------------

def page_alloc_init():
    # Globals start zeroed by BSS init; nothing functional to do.
    # Keeping the function so the call-site in arch/x86/mm/init.ad
    # reads like Linux's mem_init() flow.
    nr_pages_total        = 0
    nr_pages_free         = 0
    nr_pages_freed_total  = 0


def page_alloc_total() -> uint64:
    return nr_pages_total


def page_alloc_free_count() -> uint64:
    return nr_pages_free


def page_alloc_freed_total() -> uint64:
    # Cumulative pages ever returned via free_pages. Used by the
    # memory-leak accounting layer: in-use = total - freed_total.
    return nr_pages_freed_total


def page_alloc_in_use() -> uint64:
    # Pages currently allocated (not yet freed). Robust metric for
    # leak detection: monotonically non-decreasing unless pages leak.
    if nr_pages_total >= nr_pages_freed_total:
        return nr_pages_total - nr_pages_freed_total
    return 0
